We first recognise that parallel means that the slopes must be equal.
Rearranging the equation, we get:

\begin{align*}
x-2y &= 2\\
x-2 &= 2y\\
y&= \frac{x-2}{2}\\
y &= \frac{1}{2} x - 1.\end{align*}

So that means we are looking for points along the curve with slope equal
to $\frac{1}{2}$. To get those points, we need the derivative of the
curve:

\begin{align*}
{\frac{{\rm d}}{{\rm d}x}} (y) &= {\frac{{\rm d}}{{\rm d}x}} \left(\frac{x-4}{x+4}\right)\end{align*}

Using the quotient rule, we get:

\begin{align*}
u(x) &= x-4 & u'(x) = 1\\
v(x) &= x+4 & v'(x) = 1\end{align*}

So that means:

\begin{align*}
{\frac{{\rm d} {y}}{{\rm d}x}} &= \frac{v(x)u'(x) - u(x)v'(x)}{\left(v(x)\right)^2}\\
&= \frac{(x+4)\cdot (1) - (x-4) \cdot(1)}{\left(x+4\right)^2}\\
&= \frac{8}{\left(x+4\right)^2}\end{align*}

We are interested in points where the derivative is $\frac{1}{2}$

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} &= \frac{8}{\left(x+4\right)^2}\\
\left(x+4\right)^2 &= 16\\
x+4 &= \pm 4\\
x &= 0 , -8\end{align*}

This means we have to tackle two potential $x$ values. At $x=0$, we
have:

\begin{align*}
y &= \frac{0-4}{0+4} = -1\end{align*}

At $x=-8$, we have:

\begin{align*}
y &= \frac{-8-4}{-8+4} = \frac{-12}{-4} = 3\end{align*}

So that means the tangent lines are are looking for are: for $x=0$.

\begin{align*}
y &= \frac{1}{2}(x-0) +(-1)\\
&= \frac{1}{2}x - 1\\end{align*}

and for $x=-8$

\begin{align*}
y &= \frac{1}{2}(x-(-8)) + 3\\
&= \frac{1}{2} (x+8) +  3\\
&= \frac{1}{2} x +  7\\end{align*}
